rComments: Started my masters wanting to do C&T more than anything. Now, not so much. Ratto comes off arrogant - likes to one-up student's questions in a way that makes him sound brilliant but is rarely helpful in explaining tougher concepts. Has his PhD student do all the "lecturing", i.e. 5 quotes from the readings. Good readings, but I regret the course.

Matt Ratto is one of the best profs ever had. His readings and assignments are engaging, thoughtfully selected and designed. I've learned a huge amount from his class and would highly recommend him. He's great at leading a class discussion and listens attentively to students. I am totally confused by the negative comments below.

I just didn't feel this class was his priority. I think this is a prof that's very successful, smart and, well, busy and a side effect of that is that maybe those master level classes and students tend to be pushed to the side. Anyway, when he was on, he was on and great, but don't expect any hand holding.
He does have a considerable level of knowledge about his chosen field, but proceed with caution: he can be quite arrogant and has little tolerance for people that he doesn't respond well to.

He has a great deal of knowledge, but that's a small part of being a good educator. His ego is very "brittle", and gets in the way of his being really effective. He has little patience for students who don't "get it." He could do well to clearly establish expectations early, and make himself more available to students outside of class time.

he's a good guy. does his best with material that is very challenging to teach. some students either understand the value of learning research methodologies, or they don't. it's hard to change that. outside of class, his research projects are very innovative and interesting. one of the better profs at UofT's iSchool.
He is the hottest male prof I have ever had in a computer related subject.
